                <h3> Explain Me Please I Want To Purchase Bitcoins </h3>
                <p> First before you buy bitcoins, you must understand the concept of wallets. </p>
                <P> For those who are unfamiliar with the inner workings and quirks of Bitcoin you should note that there aren’t actually any bitcoins stored in your wallet. A bitcoin is really nothing more than a balance recorded in a publically shared database. Transactions are simply orders broadcasted to the Bitcoin network to transfer some of your balance from your bitcoin address to someone else’s. The way you prove to the network that you own the bitcoins associated with a particular address is by signing your transactions with the private key that matches that address. Think of a Bitcoin wallet more like a keychain. </P>
                <p> A bitcoin address looks something like this : 1BvBMSEYstWetqTFn5Au4m4GFg7xJaNVN2 </p>
                <p> A private key  look something like this: E9873D79C6D87DC0FB6A5778633389F4453213303DA61F20BD67FC233AA33262 </p>
                <h5> Types of Wallets </h5>
                <p> There are 3 major kinds of Bitcoin wallets we will be discussing:  online wallets, software wallets, and hardware wallets. We will start with wallets which are the easiest to set up but offer the least security and go up to wallets which are the hardest to set up but offer the most trust.
                <p> The first kind of wallet is a online wallet. This is the easiest wallet to use but offers the least security and trust. One pro of online wallets is that you can access them from anywhere, regardless of which device you are using. Some trade-offs of using an online wallet is that your private keys are stored on another server. This could lure hackers to steal your private keys, and hence your money. For instance, back in 2014 hackers store approximately $460 million from Mt. Gox, a popular Bitcoin exchange at the time. I personally only recommend storing bitcoins on a online wallet if you have a small quantity of them. </p>
                <p> Some examples of online wallets are: <a href="https://blockchain.info/" target="blank"> Blockchain.info</a>, <a href="https://www.coinbase.com/"" target="blank"> Coinbase</a>, <a href="https://greenaddress.it/en/" target="blank"> Green Address</a> and <a href="https://www.bitgo.com/" target="blank"> BitGo</a>. </p>

                <p> The second kind of wallet is a software wallet. A software wallet is a wallet installed on your computer which you have control of. You have access to your private and public key. Software wallets are available for desktop platforms as well as mobile platforms. The reference client, or the standard client in which all other wallet platforms are based on is called Bitcoin Core. This is all well and dandy except for one problem. The blockchain download. The current size of the bitcoin blockchain is more than 100GB in size. This is a real problem if you have limited storage space and limited bandwidth. </p>

                <p> Thankfully, most software clients are lightweight clients. This means they only download and communicate the pieces of information on the blockchain which matter to your Bitcoin addresses and keys. Software wallets provide more security than web wallets but greater accessibility than hardware wallets. However, one thing to note is that they are only as secure as the computer they are stored on since the keys are on the computer. Malware on your computer can comprimise your private keys. Once you download the wallet software, it synchronizes with the network by downloading the blockchain. Once it is done, simply follow the on screen instructions. I believe software wallets are the perfect mix of security and trust as well as usability. </p>

                <p> Examples of software wallets: <a href="https://www.bitcoinarmory.com/" target="blank">Armory (requires full blockchain download)</a>, <a href="https://electrum.org/" target="blank"> Electrum </a> and <a href="https://www.exodus.io/" target="blank"> Exodus </a> </p>

                <p> The final type of wallet we will talk about is a hardware wallet. Hardware wallets are dedicated hardware that are built specifically to hold bitcoin's and keep them secure. They are slightly less user-friendly than online and software wallets, but they are more secure than software wallets and online wallets. They are great for storing large amounts of cryptocurrency and offer alot of control. One disadvantage is that hardware wallets are in extremely high demand and are sold out often. Amazon is normally your best option to get one, however note that it may take a while to arrive due to demand. </p>

                <p> Examples of hardware wallets: <a href="https://www.ledgerwallet.com/" target="blank"> Ledger</a>, <a href="https://trezor.io/"> Trezor</a> and <a href="https://www.keepkey.com/" target="blank"> Keep Key </a> </p>
                <p> They are also a few other kinds of ways to store Bitcoin such as cold storage (paper wallets) and brain wallets. I will not be talking about them because they are very quirky and not used very commonly. If you are curious, here are a few links to learn more: <a href="https://www.bitcoin.com/guides/setting-up-your-own-cold-storage-bitcoin-wallet" target="blank"> Cold Storage</a> and <a href="https://www.coindesk.com/how-to-create-a-brain-wallet/" target="blank"> Brain Wallet</a> </p>

                <h5> How to buy Bitcoins? </h5>

                <p> They are many ways to purchase bitcoins. We will be going through some of them. </p>

                <h5> Buy with a credit card </h5>
                <p> One thing to note: buying bitcoins with a credit card is a relatively new service because previously credit card transactions were partially reversible by the bank. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li> <a href="https://www.coinbase.com/" target="blank"> Coinbase </a> <br> Coinbase is currently the largest Bitcoin exchange in the world. One of the main reasons for this is because of the exchanges ease of use. Coinbase has a very simple and elegant user interface which is accessible to anyone. Coinbase is also a very established exchange and currently has 18 million users every month. Just like any other exchange, Coinbase requires one to get their ID verified before they finalize an order. The good news is that the verification time is not much slower than other major exchanges. One thing to note is that if you would like to trade a higher quantity of Bitcoin and want cheaper fees, you can should use the exchange GDAX. GDAX is actually owned by Coinbase and you can use your Coinbase login on GDAX. Some cons of Coinbase are its lackluster customer support and relativily high fees. </li>

                    <li> <a href="https://www.bitstamp.net/" target="blank"> BitStamp</a> <br> BitStamp is one of the most highly rated places to buy Bitcoin online with a credit card. This is one of the cheapest exchanges to trade USD and EUR, especially if you are trading in high volumes. Everything about this exchange is fast. </li>

                </ul>


                <h5> Buy with cash </h5>

                <p> Buying bitcoin with cash is good for people who want to remain anonymous and stay off exchange records. </p>

                <ul>
                    <li> <a href="https://localbitcoins.com/" target="blank">LocalBitcoins</a> <br> LocalBitcoins is the largest peer to peer Bitcoin exchange. LocalBitcoins pairs customers with Bitcoin sellers in your vicinity. You can buy bitcoins in 2 main ways: arranging a point to meet and paying with cash or doing a transfer to the sellers bank (different for different countries). One trade-off between having high privacy is that you must pay a significant higher fee for purchasing. LocalBitcoin may also be a hub for criminals. </li>

                    <li> <a href="https://www.bitquick.co/" target="blank"> BitQuick</a> <br> BitQuick is similar to LocalBitcoins, however it only operates in the US and only does peer to peer exchanges using cash deposit. One pro to BitQuick is that bitcoin purchases are quick and are delivered usually in a hour or two. </li>

                    <li> <a href="Coinatmradar.com" target="blank"> Coinatmradar</a> <br> Coinatmradar is a map of over 1500 bitcoin ATMS in over 65 countries. A Bitcoin ATM usually accepts cash in exchange for bitcoins sent to your public address. </li>

                </ul>

                <h5> Buy with a bank transfer </h5>

                <p> Buying with a bank transfer is probably the easiest way to acquire large amounts of Bitcoin relatively quickly (3 - 4 days) </p>

               <ul>

                    <li> <a href="https://www.kraken.com/" target="blank"> Kraken</a> <br> Kraken is a major exchange which is highly audited and used by professionals. This site is best for pros trading via bank transfer. They are many currencies one can use to buy Bitcoin. </li>

                    <li> <a href="https://gemini.com/" target="blank"> Gemini </a> <br> Gemini is a exchange based in the US founded by the Winklevoss Twins. Gemini is known for its low fees and trustworthiness. It is also highly rated for its good customer service. One con is that it is not yet available in all US states and is somewhat confusing. </li>

                    <li> <a href="https://cex.io/" target="blank"> CEX.io </a> <br> CEX.io is a major exchange known for its diverse range of services. They currently have over a million users and accept many currencies. Wire transfers and credit cards are both accepted. </li>

              </ul>

